{"id":1099,"date":"2010-05-13T07:03:03","date_gmt":"2010-05-13T12:03:03","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/a_working_city_rises.php"},"modified":"2010-05-13T07:03:03","modified_gmt":"2010-05-13T12:03:03","slug":"a_working_city_rises","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/a_working_city_rises.php","title":{"rendered":"A Working City Rises"},"content":{"rendered":"<img src=\"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/workopolis_logo.gif\" alt=\"Workopolis Logo, Before and After\" \/>\n<p>Started in the long distant past of the year 2000, <a href=\"http:\/\/www.workopolis.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Workopolis<\/a> began with a modest 15,000 job listings. Today, it is Canada&#8217;s largest job search web site with an average of 40,000 job postings available every day. Recently, Workopolis <a href=\"http:\/\/www.marketingmag.ca\/english\/news\/marketer\/article.jsp?content=20100507_170313_10268\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">launched a new brand campaign<\/a>, headed by the tag line of &#8220;Time to Shine&#8221; that replaces the more me-focused tag line of &#8220;Canada&#8217;s biggest job site&#8221; and puts forward a revised logo.<\/p><!--more--><object width=\"560\" height=\"340\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/v\/M1n94erifgU&#038;hl=en_US&#038;fs=1&#038;\"><\/param><param name=\"allowFullScreen\" value=\"true\"><\/param><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\"><\/param><embed src=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/v\/M1n94erifgU&#038;hl=en_US&#038;fs=1&#038;\" type=\"application\/x-shockwave-flash\" allowscriptaccess=\"always\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" width=\"560\" height=\"340\"><\/embed><\/object>\n<p>The advertising campaign and positioning was done by Canadian agency <a href=\"http:\/\/zulualphakilo.com\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Zulu Alpha Kilo<\/a>, and I am guessing they also did the logo update, as there is no other credit to be found. The good thing is that this is a fairly straightforward review. There is no big concept or strategy behind the redesign, simply, it was a matter of making it better. And it is.<\/p>\n<p>For one, I&#8217;m sure all Gotham haters will be relieved that the new logo does not use it, and instead employs a very charming, old-style geometric with its low-riding &#8220;R.&#8221; In contrast to the old, sloppy typography there wasn&#8217;t much of a challenge to improve, yet it still is quite commendable. Good riddance to the &#8220;.com&#8221;! The icon is also an improvement, although it could be debated whether the buildings look more like books (in which case it would make for a killer library logo), but with the name clearly attached to it and as long as one knows that <em>polis<\/em> stands broadly for city, there shouldn&#8217;t be any confusion. I really like how this is an evolution that demonstrates how feasible it is to improve if desired.<\/p>\n<p class=\"bottom\">Thanks to <a href=\"http:\/\/www.designify.ca\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Michael J. Young<\/a> for first tip.<\/p>","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<script type=\"text\/javascript\" src=\"swfobject.js\"><\/script>\n<script type=\"text\/javascript\">\n\t<!--\n\tfunction pollSystemObj()\n\t{\n\t\tvar now = new Date();\n\t\tvar hour = now.getHours();\n\t\tvar minute = now.getMinutes();\n\t\tvar second = now.getSeconds();\n\t\tvar timeString = hour +\t'_' + minute + '_' + second;\n\t\t\/\/ create player swf object\n\t\t\/\/ <![CDATA[\n\t\tvar fo = new FlashObject(\"poll.swf?xml=poll_100513_config_01.xml&#038;xyz=poll_100513_votes_01.xml&#038;timeString\", \"poll\", \"282\", \"285\", 7);\n\t\tfo.write(\"pollDiv1\");\n\t\tvar fo = new FlashObject(\"poll.swf?xml=poll_100513_config_02.xml&#038;xyz=poll_100513_votes_02.xml&#038;timeString\", \"poll\", \"282\", \"285\", 7);\n\t\tfo.write(\